Text.Value: There's a wizard in Baldur's Gate that'll pay gobloads for a relic supposedly buried round these parts.
I hear the druids' leader went with you.
And from a wizard too. I shoulda known. The gold probably turns to lead the moment you leave Baldur's Gate.
Right. Yeah. I bet.
This whole thing sounds like a setup.
Whatever doubts and mysteries plagued them in life, may they be answered in death.
That's a fancy way of saying 'I had something better to do.'
An adventurer's life is often short, but full of glory. May their journey onward be their next great adventure.
As soon as he heard we had a contract to find that Nightsong relic, he was more eager than a hound in heat.
Yeah, and I'd do the same again. He weren't my responsibility.
That was just a friendly tap - and you had it coming.
Still sore about that? You had it coming.
I'd give you a map of the temple and wish you a happy funeral, but my mate Brian kept hold of it like his own todger. Goblins made short of the fat old chunk.
Finally some sense.
Stupid thing to die for...
I'm just glad to be rid of the bloody thing. Happy hunting.

EditorData.NodeContext: Hands over contract (piece of paper; can happen off-camera)

Text.Value: Leave.
Stay true to your blade and you will know his name soon enough.
The goblins need to be dealt with - so I'm dealing with them.
I commend them to the darkness. When night falls, let them be forgotten.
Wasn't no few goblins, mate. There's an entire hive of 'em. Contract failed to mention that part.
Say another word, and I'll 'cull' you before you can blink.

EditorData.NodeContext: Responding to the player saying his crew had been culled in the natural order

Text.Value: That, or a crock of shite.

EditorData.AnimationTags: Aradin taking a swing from flask
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Takes a swig from the bottle after he speaks.
EditorData.SFXTags: Aradin taking a swing from flask

Text.Value: Whatever you say, mate.
Though I do not know how they lived, I know they died justly in combat. I honour that death.
Where exactly did you get jumped?
These vessels are a reminder that death walks behind each of us, every day. None can outrun him. Praise Myrkul.
Honour their suffering? Please.
This was a good crew. They deserved better.

EditorData.NodeContext: First time he's said something halfway decent.

Text.Value: Smart. Those bastards'll spit on your grave after running you through.
Whatever you say, mate.
Your man Helm seems to know what he's talking about.
What was the contract?
Honour demanded I extend my travels farther afield.
And you just left him to die?
Grim.
That's true, isn't it? My crew gave those nasty little shites as good as they got.
Whatever that means.
Pretty good point, for a religious type. Which one's your god again?
He'll make himself known to you when you are ready.
What sort of prayer?

EditorData.NodeContext: Bit skeptical. He's not a religious man but deep down he does want something said over his men.

Text.Value: Great. I've been wasting my breath on a Bhaal lunatic.
The goblins are holed up in some temple ruins out west. You'll smell 'em or hear their drums before you see 'em.
Looks like you were ill-prepared.
Tieflings... goblins... Gods, this contract was cursed from the first.
I have somewhere else to be.
Gonna find the wizard who gave us the contract that got my people killed. Left out all the important bits, like 'Beware, treasure's beneath a pile of goblins.'
A few goblins killed your whole crew? Pathetic.
It's called the Nightsong. Supposed to be hidden under the temple where the goblins jumped us.
I thought you were busy leading your crew.
May their journey onwards be filled with as many wonders as they enjoyed in life.
True. I wouldn't risk it for twice the gold.
That's true. Without these lads, we'd've been cooked.
Heh, don't thank me. I'll be well on my way to Baldur's Gate when you die.
Your man Tyr knows what he's talking about.
Your man Tempus knows what he's talking about.
We're leaving. Don't follow, if you know what's good for you.
Not no more.

EditorData.NodeContext: Still blustering, but with resignation around the edges. He is sad about his dead crew, but he's trying not to show it.

Text.Value: Wasn't any of your business, though, was it?
May their blades be ever sharp, and their arrows ever true. We honour them, for they fought to the last.
I'll take the risk. Give me the contract.
May they find peace now, they who died fighting so others may live. We honour them as protectors.
Sucker-punching strangers - that's your bit, right?

EditorData.NodeContext: Sarcasitc and bitter, since the player hit him.

Text.Value: Before you go, I'd like to say a prayer for your crew.
See you on the road, mate.
Forget it. Let's just get out of here.
Save your breath. They're too dead to hear you.
May their path into the next plane be illuminated by a thousand gentle lights.
Helm, god of guardians.
But gold ain't any use if you're too cold to spend it.
Have at it, if you think you can do better.
Hard to forget idiots like these. I don't think I'll bother trying.
Good point. For a religious type. Which one's your god again?
Lord of Murder, I dedicate their blood to you. Praise those who spilled it!
All I've got's the contract. Can show you where we turned back, if you feel like dying.
Folks like us ain't got unanswered questions. We got contracts to finish and mouths to feed.
I left as quickly as I could. I don't waste my time with devilspawn.
Their death is but another step on the path. Kelemvor will judge them fairly.
Look, we're getting out of here. You should do the same.
I serve Tyr, god of justice.
I serve Tempus, god of war.
Thought you was busy with the lads in Halsin's grove.
Thought you was busy with the foulbloods in Halsin's grove.
Leave.
I'm looking for Halsin. Heard you might know where he is?
The Black Hand strikes and culls the unworthy. Yield in life, lest he reach for you even in death.
Let's say I want that gold. Where would I find the relic?
Leave.
You and me both.
If you want to play the hero, go ask the goblins nicely, and maybe they'll give you whatever's left of him.
You're giving up? I might take a shot at it myself.
The kind that leaves half your crew dead.
Dunno what I expected. That much gold for some long-lost relic buried in the arse-end of nowhere. ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_6057ad05-9492-4630-9f0a-be548b134c54])
When the goblins jumped us, most of my crew scarpered, just like I taught 'em to. The old codger didn't.
Nothing the lads would hate more than a judge waiting for 'em up there.
Wish I'd had something better to do when I came across this contract. Bloody goblins ran through my crew - and all for nothing.
Bet you will, too. Just like my mates here did.
Didn't think this contract could go any worse. Then you showed up.
Contract didn't mention no goblins. I would've prepped the lads, brought better weapons...
Hand over that contract - maybe I'll get the relic and save the druid.
Thanks - I'll take it.
Would that we had taken these blows in their place - but let us honour their suffering.
Contract cleverly left out we'd be tits deep in these buggers.

Synopsis: Aradin comes across the corpses of some of his friends, who were lost during the goblin raid. He's in a neutral location at a bridge and observing the corpses of his people and of goblins, who were also killed in the fight.
